The infection is minor and will likely resolve with oral antibiotics.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the open disclosure requirements in this situation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Formal disclosure is required as harm has occurred","No disclosure needed as this is an expected complication","Disclosure only required if infection worsens","Informal mention during ward round is sufficient","Documentation alone without discussion is adequate"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct response is that \u003Cstrong\u003Eformal disclosure is required as harm has occurred\u003C/strong\u003E. Even though the port-site infection is a known complication and relatively minor, any adverse event resulting in harm requires open disclosure, regardless of whether it was preventable or expected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENo disclosure needed as this is an expected complication\u003C/strong\u003E - The fact that a complication was expected does not remove the obligation for open disclosure\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDisclosure only required if infection worsens\u003C/strong\u003E - The severity of harm does not determine whether disclosure is needed; all harmful events require disclosure\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInformal mention during ward round is sufficient\u003C/strong\u003E - Open disclosure requires a formal, documented discussion in an appropriate setting\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDocumentation alone without discussion is adequate\u003C/strong\u003E - Written documentation is necessary but does not replace the need for explicit discussion with the patient\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe open disclosure process should include explaining the infection, its likely course, treatment plan, expression of regret, and any measures to prevent future occurrences. The discussion should be documented in the medical record.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Open disclosure is required for all adverse events resulting in harm, even if the outcome was an expected complication.","Near-miss events that did not result in harm do not require formal open disclosure.","System errors causing harm require open disclosure even if no individual was at fault."],"references":["Finlay AJ, Stewart CL, Parker M. Open disclosure: ethical, professional and legal obligations, and the way forward for regulation. Med J Aust. 2013 May 6;198(8):445-8. doi: 10.5694/mja12.10734. PMID: 23641998. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23641998/","Medical Board of Australia. Good medical practice: a code of conduct for doctors in Australia [online]. 2020 [Cited 2025 Jan 15]. Available at: https://www.medicalboard.gov.au/codes-guidelines-policies/code-of-conduct.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65745"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18947"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65745"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-20T20:10:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-20T20:12:02+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11681"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80457"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"18","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/18"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\u